tweet: I‚Äôve often said that the null hypothesis should be that the market is efficient.  Not that I *think* it actually is, but it re-frames the question.  Instead of saying, ‚Äú2s10s looks historically flat,‚Äù I have to say, ‚Äúwhy is it flat?  What does the market know that I don‚Äôt?"

tweet: In the current environment, 2s10s might look historically flat.  Or the value spread might look historically wide.  But are the readings extreme enough to overcome all the things we *don‚Äôt* know?
